 Find the slope of the line $2x + 3y = 21$ to use it as the slope of the line through the points (2, -9) and (j, 17). </think>
\begin{align*}2x + 3y &= 21\\3y &= -2x + 21&&\gray{\text{Subtract}\,2x\,\text{from both sides.}}\\y &= \frac{-2}{3}x + 7&&\gray{\text{Divide both sides by 3.}}\\m &= \frac{-2}{3}&&\gray{\text{The equation is now in slope-intercept form.}}\end{align*}
<answer>From the equation, the slope of the line is $\frac{-2}{3}$.  $\frac{17-(-9)}{j-2}=\frac{-2}{3}$ Let's cross multiply: $17+9 = \frac{-2}{3}j-\frac{-4}{3} \times 2$, which gives us $52=\frac{-2}{3}j+\frac{4}{3}$ Subtract $\frac{4}{3}$ from both sides: $52-\frac{4}{3}=-\frac{2}{3}j$ take on LCM and solve: $j=11$. </answer>

The two lines are parallel, so they have the same slope. The slope of the line can be found by the formula $m = \frac{y_2 - y_1}{x_2 - x_1}$. For the given line $2x + 3y = 21$, we can rearrange it to slope-intercept form $y = mx + b$ to find the slope. <end think> {eq}m = -\frac{2}{3}

